---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Certification — Plain Theory Labs";
---

<BaseLayout title="Certification — Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>

  <!-- How certification works -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Certification</span>
      <p>
        PTL scores AI compute infrastructure on a 0.0 to 1.0 scale against a
        documented methodology. The performance tier — BASELINE through FRONTIER —
        is shorthand for where the score lands. The score is the truth; the tier
        is the label. The certification is a longitudinal record, not a one-time
        audit. Year one is a baseline. Year three is a dataset.
      </p>

      <hr class="rule" />

      <span class="section-label">How certification works</span>
      <p>
        <em>Data collection.</em> You provide a Slurm scheduler export and basic
        facility information — cooling type, location, carbon accounting method.
        Additional engines require additional data. Every data requirement is
        documented before the engagement begins.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Engine analysis.</em> Each engine runs independently against your data.
        ACE grades GPU efficiency. COOL grades cooling performance. FLUX grades
        carbon accounting methodology. PACE grades scheduler policy. CORE grades
        hardware-workload fit. Every finding includes a confidence label and
        disclosed assumptions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>GRADE certification.</em> Engine scores are weighted and aggregated into
        a composite. The composite determines your certification tier. Engines you
        have not yet provided data for are excluded from the composite — partial
        certification is meaningful certification.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>ATLAS recommendations.</em> ATLAS ranks the actions most likely to
        improve your certification in the next assessment. Priority is determined
        by gap size, engine weight, and operational impact. You receive a ranked
        action plan alongside your certification.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Certification tiers -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Certification tiers</span>
      <p>
        PTL scores clusters on a 0.0 to 1.0 scale. The performance tier is
        shorthand for where the score lands. The number is the truth — the
        tier is the label.
      </p>
      <div class="tier-table">
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">FRONTIER</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">All five engines · PTL Score ≥ 0.85</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">OPTIMIZED</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Four or more engines · PTL Score ≥ 0.70</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">CAPABLE</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Three or more engines · PTL Score ≥ 0.60</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">DEVELOPING</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Two or more engines · PTL Score ≥ 0.45</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">BASELINE</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">ACE only — first scored assessment</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">PENDING</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">No engines complete</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        MIT Supercloud scored 0.450 on its first assessment — DEVELOPING tier.
        The ATLAS engine identified GPU scheduler configuration as the
        highest-impact improvement, specific enough to act on the same week.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The longitudinal record -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">The longitudinal record</span>
      <p>
        Certification is most valuable over time. An organization that improves from
        BASELINE to DEVELOPING to CAPABLE across three annual assessments has something
        regulators, funders, and procurement offices can evaluate. PTL maintains the
        certification record. You own the findings.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Start a certification — dark closing -->
  <section class="pilot-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label-dark">Start a certification</span>
      <p>
        We are taking three pilot organizations this quarter. A pilot begins with your
        Slurm scheduler export and basic facility information. We run the analysis,
        deliver private findings to your team, and work through what the results mean
        together. You decide what to do with it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The findings belong to your organization. We keep the methodology.
      </p>
      <a href="mailto:jesus@plaintheory.org" class="cta-link-light" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        Start a pilot
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
